messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Here is the analysis based on the provided files.

- Full HTTP request path (path must start with / and use {param} for path params if any):
  - /users/reset

  Explanation: The route is defined in routes/userRoutes.js as router.post('/reset', resetPassword) and in index.js it is mounted with app.use('/users', userRoutes.js). Therefore the full path is /users/reset. There are no path parameters in this endpoint.

- All HTTP methods acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: Only POST is defined for this endpoint (router.post('/reset', resetPassword)). There is no catch-all or .all() defined for this path.

- HEAD acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: There is no explicit HEAD handler for /users/reset, and there is no GET handler for this path either. Express will not automatically enable HEAD for a route that only has a POST handler.

- POST acceptable:
  - True

  Explanation: The route explicitly defines router.post('/reset', resetPassword), so POST is supported.

- OPTIONS acceptable:
  - True

  Explanation: The app uses the CORS middleware globally (app.use(cors())). This middleware handles preflight OPTIONS requests, so OPTIONS is effectively supported for this endpoint.

- TRACE acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: There is no TRACE handler defined in the code.

- GET acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: There is no GET handler for /users/reset.

- PUT acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: There is no PUT handler for /users/reset.

- DELETE acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: There is no DELETE handler for /users/reset.

- PATCH acceptable:
  - False

  Explanation: There is no PATCH handler for /users/reset.

Summary:
- Endpoint path: /users/reset
- Methods: POST is supported; HEAD/GET/PUT/DELETE/PATCH/TRACE not supported; OPTIONS is supported via CORS preflight handling. Path has no parameters.
